column42: GASOHOL GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: While delivering at Warwick Gulf driver had dual hoses delivering unleaded regular gasoline into UST's #1 & #2 which were baffled. Delivery to tank #1 was completed at which time, driver disconnected delivery hose and fitting and began to stow back on truck. Product started to "fountain" out of the fill pipe of tank #1 as product continued to flow into tank #2. Initial investigation reveals that driver neglected to replace and secure the fill cap on tank #1 after completion of delivery which allowed the pressure from filling tank #2 to back up into tank #1 casuing the product to vent out of the uncapped fill hole. Flow of product was immediately secured with onboard spill kit deployed to contain the spill on concrete fill area. Local fire department responded to complete containment. Abenaqui Carriers called Response Environmental, Worcester, MA who contracted with Fleet Environmental to provide emergency reponse and clean-up. No product entered any outfills as verified by Warwick Fire Department. Scene was cleaned and secured with all waste transported for proper disposal.
column169: Driver to be placed under letter of investigation and to review proper loading procedures paying close attention to delivering with multiple hoses.

column168: On November 4, 2007, at approximately 1015 hours, a railway tankcar ACFX 87288, loaded with Petroleum Distillates, flammable, UN1268 PG I, was reported leaking at the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) Shreveport Louisiana yard. The tank car was discovered leaking from the bottom outlet valve (BOV) and cap. The shipper secured FRA movement approval to return this car to origin location for off loading and decon. Forwarded empty car to tank car shop. There were no injuries, no damage to the environment.        Code: 148  NARRI: 5(5+5+0(x(2+0)=100
column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: Tractor/trailer combination (cargo tank)bulk, non spec cargo tank EMPTY; involved in crash.  Unit struck slow moving State Of Louisiana DOTD (Department of Transportation & Development)"Bump Truck" fitted with impact attenuator and signage stating "CAUTION - SLOW MOVING VEHICLE AHEAD". LA - DOTD vehicle following motorgrader which was removing sod and vegitation from left inside shoulder of westbound lanes of Interstate Hwy I-20 in Madison Parish, Louisiana.  Vehicle # 1 (Carrier) struck right rear of Vehicle # 2 (LA -DOTD) unit; Vehicle # 1 out of control, crossed median, entered Eastbound lanes of I-20, struck eastbound vehicle #3, combination of Private Passenger Pick Up truck pulling travel trailer.  Vehicle # 1 overturned after secondary impact.  Right side fuel tank was ruptured spraying diesel fuel onto surrounding vegitation.  Damage to vehicle(s) # 3 so extensive that fuel/gasoline tank ruptured in crash; vehicle # 2 ignited causing fuels soaked grass vegitation to catch fire, ensuing blaze caused diesel fuel to ignite and burned overturned tractor of vehicle # 1.  Cargo tank front skin and insulation was burned in blaze, vessel did not burn, no product in cargo tank at time of crash.
column169: Investigation of responding agency(s) LA State Police incomplete and not available at this time.  Condition of driver of vehicle # 1 is such that statement has not been obtained at this time.  Supplemental information to be submitted upon receipt and completion of investigation by agency(s) involved and company representatives.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While loading, two cartons, each containing four, 4-liter glass receptacles, were damaged by the forklift.  One receptacle in each carton was damaged.  Approximately 8 liters of free product were released and evaporated.  Alliance Airlines personnel placed the two damaged cartons, with entire contents into a salvage drum pending disposal coordination.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Alliance Airlines will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: At approximately 0745 hours, the loader of the rail car noticed that styrene was leaking from the rail car’s belly valve into the rail pan.  He also noticed that the rail car sump pad was overflowing onto the ground.  He immediately worked the belly valve to stop the leak.  The loader noticed a piece of red debris that was dislodged from the rail car’s belly valve.  There was approximately 100 gallons of styrene that spilled out of the rail pan and overflowed the sump and traveled approximately 150 feet in a narrow path.  The rail car sump pump had tripped electrically and did not pump when the high level indicator was activated.  Area monitoring was conducted and it was determined that full face respirator protection was required for clean-up activities.    The styrene was channeled to a trench, flushed with water to the sump and then into the slop oil tank for reprocessing.  Approximately 92-gallons of styrene were recovered.  The total amount spilled was approximately 756 pounds, which did not exceed the Reportable Quantity for styrene (CAS # 100-42-52) of 1,000 pounds.  All soil that came in contact with the styrene was excavated and will be ultimately disposed of off-site.
column169: The cause of the leak was debris lodged in the belly valve of the rail car that prevented the valve from closing completely.  This combined with the sump pump malfunction caused the overflow.  The corrective actions that have been taken are for the Operator to make sure the belly valve is closed completely before loading starts and the Operator must check the sump pump by switching to manual mode to check for proper operation.

column168: On November 11, 2007,  at 04:24, personnel in the CSXT Yard in Montgomery, AL.  discovered ACFX220016, a loaded tank car of Anhydrous Ammonia leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Transammonia, Inc., was notified and all appropriate state notifications were made.  SWS, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid leaking from the base of the "B" end liquid valve.  Contractor personnel  tightened two of the four stud bolts that held the valve in place. They also found the plug in the valve was hand tight. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.    Cause Code:  270  NARRI:  5(5+9+0) x (2+0) = 140
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 11/06/2007 at 14:09 personnel in the CSXT Gentilly Yard discovered ECUX 355122, a loaded  tank car of Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S. leaking from the Manway area of the car. The car was isolated and shipper, local, and  state agencies  were notified. W. R. Gleason, a CSXT hazardous materials manager, was dispatched to the scene and found the car leaking from the manway when the car was moved. The manway bolts were found improperly secured, which allowed the liquid  to splash out on top the the car when the car was moved. The car was repaired by installing a new manway gasket and properly tightening the bolts on the manway. The car was then released for transportation.     Cause Code:  208  NARRI:  5 (5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A FRA inspector in the railyard reported to local operating management that ADMX 29320 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was discovered dripping product from the bottom outlet valve (BOV). ADMX 29320 was carefully isolated in the railyard for further inspection. A BNSF responder inspecting ADMX 29320 reported that the BOV was closed and sealed; and no product drips were noted at that time. A product stain was observed around the primary BOV flange. The responder found three BOV flange bolts less than tool tight by 1/8 to 1/4 turn. The flange bolts were tool tightened and no further product drips were noted afterwards. All spillage evaporated.

column168: While at unloading facility, shipment was discovered on rear of trailer with one of four boxes lying on its side, leaking.  Shipment had been loaded on floor in rear of trailer, with one of boxes loaded directly on top of another.  There was a one foot gap of open floor space left between the shipment and the trailer door.  Apparently the box on top fell off during transit as there was no other freight or dunnage to block it in.  Box fell approximately one foot, landing on its side, and rupturing the plastic bladder inside the box.  One half gallon of contents were released.  Spill was contained and cleaned up at unloading faciltiy.  Damaged box held in haz mat bay of unloading facility for disposal via environmental contractor.
column169: Notice sent to loading facility to review loading practices, use of dunnage, and proper blocking and bracing.  Notice also sent to review trailer closing procedures.  Shipment packaged adequately for transport as received from manufacturer.

column168: On November 2, 2007, at approximately 0815 hours, a railway tankcar GATX 200996, Residue: last contained Ammonia, Anhydrous, nonflammable gas, UN1005, was reported leaking at the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) Port Arthur, Texas yard. The tank car was discovered leaking from the pressure relief valve. The consignee representitive responded to the site and repaired the defective PRV.  There were no injuries, no damage to the environment.       NARRI=5(4+1+0)x(2+0)=50                                                                                      CODE=414
column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: On Monday 11/05/07 at 12:15 PM West Central FS, Inc experienced an anhydrous ammonia release. The location of the release was on county road N850 Adair, IL 61411, approximately 50 yards west of intersecting county road E2250. A pickup truck driven by West Central FS employee was pulling anhydrous ammonia tank A33 1 and was proceeding south on E2250 and turned right (West bound) onto N850. After making the turn the front left lug bolt that attaches the tank to the running gear sheared off and the left front lug bolt pulled loose from the running gear. This then allowed the front of the nurse tank to come down and make contact with the asphalt road on the driver’s side of the running gear. Before employee was able to stop the truck which was pulling the tank now partially on the ground the back two lug bolts broke loose from the running gear, separating it completely from the running gear. The nurse tank then rolled over on the asphalt crushing the safety cage which in turn broke off the liquid withdraw valve allowing ammonia to escape from the tank into the atmosphere. The tank came to a stop in the south ditch on county road N850 in the upright position.    The escaping ammonia was dissipating into the atmosphere at a rapid rate. The wind was blowing approximately 20-25 MPH to the Southeast. One person in a house directly east of county road E2250 on county road N850 as a precautionary measure was asked to evacuate. No other homes or buildings were down wind of the tank’s location. The accident occurred in a very rural area that is 100% cropland.    The Illinois State Police was immediately notified along with the Adair Fire Department. Both entities responded to the scene. The National Response Center was notified of the release at 12:23 PM. We were provided with report #853653 by Pundt. The Illinois Emergency Management Agency was then notified at 12:33 PM and we were provided Incident #H-2007-1486. The McDonough County ESDA office was then notified of the release at 12:44 PM. Dan Kreps was the ESDA coordinator that was notified, no incident 4 or report # was provided by employee.    At the scene the determination was made by the Adair Fire Department, Illinois State Police officer Todd Teal and West Central FS to allow the tank to continue to vent off the ammonia into the atmosphere. The escaping ammonia was blowing across cropland and not negatively impacting any humans or animals or the environment so the decision was made not to apply a water fog to the escaping ammonia to “Knock the ammonia plume down”. Also Officer Teal checked IL Rte 136 and the ammonia plume was not coming near the highway. The local road district commissioner was also notified of the release and he blocked off county roads N850 and E2250 to eliminate traffic from entering the incident area.    At Approximately 3:00 PM the ammonia ceased escaping from the tank as the pressure in the tank had equalized with the atmospheric pressure. This was evident by the predominate fr

THE BOLTS WILL BE CHECKED TO INSURE THEY ARE FREE OF ABNORMAL WEAR, FREE OF STRESS CRACKS AND ARE TIGHTLY SECURING THE TANK TO THE RUNNING GEAR.

column168: On November 11, 2007, at approximately 16:09 hours, a railway tankcar UTLX 802780, loaded with Ethanolamine, corrosive, UN2491 PG III, was reported leaking at the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) Shreveport Louisiana yard. The tank car was discovered leaking from the bottom outlet valve (BOV) and the BOV cap which was loose due to a  missing gasket. The shipper representative responded to the site repositioned BOV handle to closed position and secured cap with gasket .  There were no injuries, no damage to the environment, car was released to its destination.        CODE: 148  NARRI: 5(5+3+0)x(2+0)=80
column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: Traveling on Plano Road Northbound, driver checked mirror and noticed liquid on pavement behind truck and trailer.  driver immediately pulled to turn land and stopped to check for a leak coming from trailer.  Driver determined the leak was coming from the trailer, and moved trailer to abandonded parking lot adjacent to Plano Road.  Fire, police, and Univar management personnel arrived at the scende.  Driver contained any further leaking by placing absorbents and containment bucket under the trailer.  Fire department hazmat team contained and neutralized the spill.  Independent hazmat resonse team was contacted by Univar, and arrived at the scene to finish cleanup procedure and returned the waste materials to Univar facility for disposal.    Trailer leak was determined to be casused by a failed rupture disk on compartment #3.  Reupture disk was replaced, trailer was cleaned of hazardous materials by Univar, and returned to Univar facility.
column169: Rupture disks on all compartments of trailer replaced.  Also, entire trailer tested for any mechanical defect which might have caused rupture disk to fail outside of the rupture disk itself.

According to the information obtained the following occurred.  Approximately 1,129 gallons of gaseous product were released and dissipated.  Apparently the release occurred as a result of a failed man-way gasket.  AMX Environmental Evolution, LTD of Fort Worth, Texas was dispatched to repair the damaged man-way gasket.  AMX Environmental Evolution, LTD repaired the damaged gasket and secured the leak.  No cleanup was required.  No injuries or exposures were reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental and may have been the result of a failed man-way gasket, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, South Hampton Refining, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

SPILL TECHNICIANS RICKEY DAVIS JR AND MATTHEW PHILLIPS DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE INSIDE OF THE PACKAGE. THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN 4 X 1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES OF ZEP-A-LUME. DUE TO A LOOSE CLOSURE ON 3 OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLES, A TOTAL OF 3 OZ OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA TRUCK # 4333.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS DECLARED AS CORROSIVE LIQUIDS TOXIC NOS (HYDROGEN FLUORIDE AND SULFURIC ACID), CLASS 8 (6.1), UN2922, PG II, WITH THE SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED. Clean up completed by 2000 Thursday 11/8/07.

On November 11, 2007, a leaking package was detected at the Veolia 10-day intransit facility located in Baytown, TX.  The package contained broken mercury thermometers with liquid mercury and mercury contaminated debris.  When being prepared for transportation from the customer's site, the materials were placed in a plastic bag or liner and then placed in a 1G fiber box.   While in transit, the plastic bag ruptured causing a small amount of liquid to leak through the container wall.  All liquid mercury and any mercury contaminated surfaces were collected and containerized for transport to the original off-site disposal facility.
column169: Materials containing liquid mercury should not be packaged into 1G containers with plastic bags.  A plastic 1H2 container should be used to prevent to potential for a release.  All field technicians will be retrained in the proper handling and packaging of mercury and mercury containing debris in compliance with the requirements of the DOT regulations.

column168: RAM Shipment originated in ORD on DL1280/13NOV to ATL with planned connection to DL1575/13NOV to MIA.  Flight arrived into gate B-27 and shipment was scheduled to depart from A-2.     Shipment consisted of Sodium Iodide I-123, inner packages consisted of 30 lead containers (3-4” in length) in one Type A Package, Yellow II shipment, 13.2 hour half life with up to 6 days of particle release.  Each inner container contained one capsule; each capsule contained Iodide salt (solid).     During ramp transport from B-27 to B-North Bag Point, package apparently fell off bag cart and was subsequently lodged underneath a cart; unknown to the driver.  Another ramp employee alerted the tug driver to the package.  Inspection revealed, the entire contents of package were released in the ramp area on B-North (30 lead containers with pop caps; each container contained 1 capsule of material).      Immediate notification was made to the Operations Control Center (OCC) who in turn contacted the corporate Emergency Response Duty Officer  (EMDO).  Based on evaluation of the scenario and the unknown location and condition of the 30 vials, the EMDO advised the operation to contact local emergency response (fire department).  The EMDO in turn contacted the shipper at the emergency response number located on the paperwork to obtain detailed information on the contents.  After this information was confirmed, the NRC was notified.  EMDO was contacted by Sidney "Barty" Simonton of the GA EPD Radiological Response Team inquiring on the situation and offering assistance.  Sidney "Barty" Simonton took point on search and retrieval.      It was determined the majority of the spill was confined to B-North NLVR between ramp 2, 3 and gate B-36.  Twenty-nine (29) containers were recovered in various states of condition from intact to crushed.  According to GA EPD, 65% inner containers were compromised (opened) with 50% of those being crushed.  Under the direction of GA EPD, Airport FD hosed NLVR and grass area to further deplete half life (product is a salt and dilution reduced the contamination risk).      HEPACO, Delta's environmental contract service, monitored the area as needed for up to 6 days 24 hours a day. Cart and bag tug were tested and no detectable radiation was found.
column169: The requirement to secure packages of dangerous goods during all modes of transport were reviewed with Atlanta Ramp Leadership to be included in daily briefings with all personnel.  Delta will continue to evaluate to dentify any systemic problems and determine if further corrective action(s) are warrented.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling on Interstate 68 eastbound in Morgantown, West Virginia, the Slay Transportation Co. Inc. driver was involved in a fatal vehicle accident, which caused the truck to rollover off the embankment of the roadway.  The tank was damaged, which resulted in the release of approximately 180 gallons of free product to the soil along the road shoulder.  Free product was being released at approximately one gallon per minute, prior to offload and containment.  Monongalia County Emergency Management responded to assess the site.  Bayer Material Science was contacted to discuss response actions.  Weavertown Environmental Group of Carnegie, Pennsylvania was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Bayer Material Science responded to offload the damaged tanker.  Upon completion of offload, Weavertown Environnmental Group proceeded to excavate the contaminated soil from the impacted area.  The contaminated soil was containerized into three (3) rolloff boxes and transported off site, to Advanced Environmental Solutions, pending disposal.  There were no injuries or exposures related to the hazardous material.  No further action was required.
column169: In order to prevent recurrence of the incident or similar incidents, Slay Transportation Co., Inc. drivers are required to attend safety meetings.  Safety meetings address such issues as handling spills, driving hazards and job specific training.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. are required to attend DOT job specific training classes. Slay Transportation Co., Inc. addresses safety issues in their driver’s newsletter.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safety guidelines to all employees.

column168: Driver attempted to take a 90-degree left-hand turn at an elevated rate of speed with 7,500 gallons of Diesel Fuel on-board. The center of gravity was exceeded and the vehicle overturned onto its right side.  Two compartments failed resulting in a release of approximately 1,184 gallons.  Driver had very minor injuries and refused EMS treatment at the scene.  Response contractor notified and responded within 60 minutes of the incident. Fire and Police controlled scene and Response Contractor recovered all product that was released.  Power company disconnected the 7200KVA Power Line and replaced the broken power pole and blown transformer; thus restoring power to the limited area that was affected.  Vehicle was inspected by Phoenix Police Department's Commercial Vehicle Enforcement with no violations found on the vehicle. Driver was cited for failure to control vehicle.
column169: All drivers will be re-trained and informed of the dangers associated with transporting liquids in tank trucks; as well as the importance to significantly reduce speed for cornering, turns, and over uneven terrain.

column168: On 11/01/2007 personnel in the CSXT Cumberland Yard were advised by FRA Inspector they discovered UTLX 203863, a loaded tank car of Alcohols N.O.S, with an audible vapor leak from the vacuum relief devise. The car was isolated and Aventine Renewable Energy was notified. Aventine contacted SPSI to repair and test the vacuum relief device on the car. SPSI advised CSXT that the vacuum relief device had a cracked "o" ring and it was replaced.

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT,WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE  COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MW PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED AND INSTRUCTED THEM TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER FOR A MSDS AND HOLD THEPACKAGE. I ALSO NOTIFIED GREG PORTER OF THE PHL/FAA OFFICE TO REPORT THE INCIDENT AT 14:30 ON 11-14-2007. HE WAS GOING TOINVESTIGATE THE INCIDENT IN THE NEXT DAY OR SO. THE SHIPPER STATED HE WOULD BEFLYING OUT THERE TOMORROW AND HE COULD MEET WITH THEM AS WELL, SO I PASSED THAT INFORMATION ON TO THE FAA.

When Tarr Employees opened the trailer door of the Portland delivery truck/trailer combo they noticed a release had occurred.  The driver noticed the source of the leak was a tote. Immediately both drivers on site took action to stop the leaking material from going into the storm drain. A sealing magnetic mat was placed over the drain opening.  They had to remove one tote to gain access to the tote that was leaking. They noted that the 2 inch ball valve was almost a quarter of the way open and the 2 inch camlock fitting had come off. The valve was closed immediately. The Operations Manager, Harold Eveland, was notified as soon as the initial emergency procedures had been completed. When he arrived, he noticed that material was leaking into the catch basin despite the drain cover. He called Thermo Fluids on an emergency basis to come and vacuum the pool of solvent and water.  Corporate was notified and they contacted the WA State Emergency Mgt. who notified the Department of Ecology (DOE).  Harold also called the Regional Valley Fire Authority. They came and inspected the scene, were satisfied that correct emergency response procedures were being followed and left.  Thermo Fluids arrived and pumped out the catch basin and water being utilized to flush any solvent laying on the asphalt.  All of the leaking material (Solvent 140F) was captured by this process. Harold along with the Thermo Fluids rep checked additional catch basins in the immediate area and found no contamination from the spill. There was no evidence of product in any other catch basins/storm drains. The DOE arrived to inspect the area where the leak occurred.  They concurred that the area had been cleaned up as well as possible and there was no further contamination. They also inspected the tote that had been leaking and found that container integrity had been restored once the valve had been closed completely. Tarr then initiated a Corrective Action Report (CAR) and started the process on their fleet of totes to change all 2 inch ball valves to locking ball valves and all camlocks to locking camlock fittings.
column169: The maintenance Manager has been directed to change out ball valves and camlocks on all totes to reflect locking capabilities. A review of the tote filling procedures was made and are being rewritten to included pre-checks, fill procedures and post filling checks to insure everything is locked and tied.

Customers forklift driver was placing a skid in the nose of a Univar trailer. During this process the forks of the lift extened through the palllet that was to be placed.When spotting the pallet the forks struck the drum that was on a skid directly in front the forklift. The damaged drum leaked product from a small hole near the bottom chime of the container. The driver placed  drum on it's side to stop the leak. He then received help to place it into an over pack.
column169: During the incident investigation it was determined the skid that was to be placed in the front of the trailer was only 36" in length. All material handlers have been instructed to place short pallets on a 46 X 46 pallet for future shipments. This will eliminate the forks from protruding through a short skid and possibly striking another container.

column168: A DOT inspector in the railyard observed UTLX 204094 with a product stain on its side shell that emanated from the manway nozzle area atop this DOT 111A100W1 tank car. The DOT inspector notified local BNSF operating and mechanical management about this observation. The DOT inspector and a BNSF mechanical responder performed a detailed inspection of UTLX 204094. The manway seal was removed and the BNSF mechanical responder tool tightened 4 of 6 manway securement bolts that were found less than tool tight. Securement was completed around 1230 hrs. PST, 11/14/07. Spillage on the shell evaporated and no ground spillage was evident. UTLX 204094 was released to proceed to its destination and this phase of transportation was completed without further incident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Upon opening trailer at customer location, a leak was discovered.  Apparently, one (1) 350-gallon tote bin had a loose fitting safety valve, which caused the release.  Approximately 300 gallons of free product were released inside the trailer, and leaked onto the asphalt surface.  The Local Fire Department responded to contain the free product.  Hulcher Services, Inc. of Atlanta, Georgia was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, printing ink was detected within the trailer and on the asphalt surface beneath the trailer.  Hulcher Services, Inc. proceeded to apply sand to contain the free product, and used a street sweeper to recover the spent sand, and remove residual product.  The spent sand was containerized into one (1) roll-off box, to be held for disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since release was accidental, and appears to be related to a loose safety valve, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Wilson Trucking Corporation will continue to reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: A BNSF Trainmaster in the railyard observed ACFX 95967 dripping residue product from the bottom outlet area. A BNSF mechanical foreman was notified and inspected ACFX 95967 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car); finding the bottom operated bottom outlet valve (BOV) partially open with the bottom outlet closure cap (BOC) less that tool tight. The BOV was closed and the BOC was tool tightened, which ended any further product drips. All drippage evaporated. Afterwards, an adjacent tank car (SHPX 203295) in the same yard track with the same shipper origin was inspected. SHPX 203295 also had less than tool tight BOC securement and this BOC was tool tightened. No leakage from SHPX 203295 was reported.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column169: PAILS, CYLINDERS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWNS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO EASILY DAMAGED. TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OFHAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was intransit between the point of origin and the intended waste management facility.  Upon arrival at the intended waste management facility, it was discovered that a container on the vehicle had leaked allowing approximately 1 gallon of material to be released onto the floor of the van trailer and through the floor of the trailer onto the ground. Facility personnel immediately donned appropriate protective equipment and initiated appropriate response procedures.  Upon identification of the damaged container, it was determined that a 55 gallon steel drum had developed a pinhole leak due to corrosion of the drum.   The response crew collected all spill material using a suitable absorbent material and disposed of it along with the damaged drum at the intended waste management facility.
column169: All appropriate persons will be reinstructed to inspect all containers carefully for evidence of corrosion before accepting such containers.

column168: A Quality Carriers tractor tanker overturned while traveling on I-70 EB at mile marker 132 near Buckeye Lake, Ohio.  The tractor tanker did not suffer any actual release of the material as a result of the accident.  The tractor tanker became overturned on its site and blocked all 3 lanes of eastbound traffic for ~11 hours.  Local officials also closed down the westbound lane for around 5 hours.  Due to the traffic through the area, a local school canceled classes for the remainder of the day.  Upon notification to ERTS, we dispatched UST Environmental to the site.  Once on site it was determined by the Incident Command Officer (ICO-fire department chief) that a transfer of the material would be required prior to moving the damaged tanker.  UST personnel suited up into the appropriate PPE and began the transfer into a new tanker provided by Quality Carriers.  Due to the cold weather, the material became viscous.  Because of this, the ICO ordered that the tank be cut open so that the material could be more easily transfered.  Once the tank had been cut open, the materials were transferred into the undamaged tanker.  No release occurred as a result of this motor vehicle accident.  This was also a single vehicle accident.

column168: Our driver accepted a non specification cardboard 1 cubic yard capacity gaylord box filled with a material described as "Hazardous Waste Solid, N.O.S. (chromium).  When he arrived at his next customer site and opened the trailer door he discovered that the cubic yard box had split open causing a wet, watery material from the box to spill onto the trailer floor with a small quantity spilling onto the ground.  The driver utilized an on-board spill kit to contain the liquid inside the trailer.  Local fire and emergency response personnel were summoned and they stabilized the spilled material.  A private cleanup contractor was hired to clean the roadway, clean the inside of the trailer and repackage all spill related material. The duration of the spill cleanup was approximately 7 hours.  The truck then continued on without further incident.
column169: Shipper should provide better training to avoid improper descriptions of hazardous materials and improper package selections.

column168: Incident Report November 12, 2007   Subject Name: Custom N113 Release on Jim Silliman farm   On Monday, November 12th, at 10:10 pm, I received notice that there had been an NH3 release north of Emmetsburg from one of our custom application units. MaxYield employee Ryan Stokes was custom applying NH3 (Anhydrous Ammonia) on the farm owned by Jim Silliman about 3 miles North of Emmetsburg. The address of where Ryan made his calls and which was the closest to the release would be 3272 470th Aye, Emmetsburg, Iowa. This “safe zone” was at the end of Jim Silliman’ s lane located about a ‘/2 south of the release. The CAT tractor Ryan was operating is equipped with auto- steer and while Ryan was observing the application process he suddenly seen there was a cloud of NH3 vapor near the rear of the applicator. Ryan quickly turned the flow off but product continued to stream out. Thinking correctly, Ryan then turned the tractor upwind to try to get in a safe position. Since there was very little (if any) wind that evening, the exodus of product was hanging in the air and becoming overwhelming. It was going to be a challenge to escape the vapor cloud which had now encircled the cab. Ryan instinctively took evasive maneuvers with the tractor to try to pull past and away from the cloud and position the tractor correctly. He did this by shifting to higher gears to gain more speed and by making right angles to escape the heavy flow. My investigation the following morning showed that Ryan traveled about 800’ in various directions to attempt to outrun the cloud. Since the valve was pointed forward, Ryan was hoping he would get the flow to shoot another direction while he made his exit from the cab and the area. His tactic worked relatively well and he was able to then quickly stop the tractor, put it in neutral, turn off the ignition switch, and exit the cab. Ryan then ran to a nearby gravel road where he then called 911. His next call was to his supervisor Gerald Zwiefel who immediately notified me on my cell to help in finding solutions and to make the necessary notifications. I then called Ryan back to get further details so I could relay the information. Ryan said the Fire Department and Law Enforcement were now on the scene.   After getting the details as far as we knew them at the time, I then called the National Response Center at 800-424-8802 at 10:22 pm and talked with a Mr. Snowden to inform him of the release as required by law when any NH3 release is greater than 100 lb. (about 20 gal). NRC Report number:   854379. My next call was to PERS 800-633-8253 at 10:30 pm where I talked with Kevin to inform them of what we were doing up to this point. Kevin said it sounded like we had things under control and said I should call again if we run into any complications. At 10:35 I called the Iowa DNR 515- 28 1-8694 to inform them of what we had and steps that were being taken at this time. They will page the necessary people that need to be notified in their agenc
column169: A solution to reducing repeat incidents is actually 2-part.   One, the coupler needs to be tight without chances of wire or chain getting into the threads to impede the connection. We will implement a better way to connect these plastic caps company wide. In our shop the following morning we tested this theory by hooking up a connection exactly like the one in the field. It was interesting to note that when a connection is properly made, it takes 2 ‘/4 turns to separate completely. When the coupler was tightened when jammed against a plastic cap retaining   Wire, it was separated in a 1/2 turn. This test was done only to show that the wire and/or chain could cause a problem if it was not seen, and happened to be resting in one of the thread grooves. Two, the excess flow valves need to be connected in a way which will allow them to do their job. I called Davis Equipment and they were well aware of the problem we face. Currently 2 products are being introduced into the market to help with this. Continental is designing one to be tethered to the tractor by a cable so in the event of a detachment, the line would pull the auto-shutoff in the closed position. Davis Equipment felt farmers would not be in favor of this because they do not want to be attached directly to the tank. The second device is designed by Squibb and is an electronic device which requires power to be in the “open” position. Once the power in interrupted in any way, the valve slams shut. Davis Equipment looked to be more in favor of this safety valve but also added it may be quite expensive and felt unless it was mandated by law, that it would not be accepted by the general public.   Footnote: Working with a pressurized product such as NH3 requires special attention to detail. Connections must be proper, PPE in place, etc. Any flaw in the network of equipment can result in an unfavorable outcome. We were fortunate this incident happened in the middle of the field and no injuries occurred or environmental concerns were affected   Product Lost: Estimate 410 2allon. Ryan Stokes, the operator at the time knew exactly how many acres were covered and how many gallon were left in the tanks.   No creeks, ponds, or rivers nearby. Clear skies, 40 degrees, calm winds. Chiseled soybean stubble.   This information is correct based on my observation and discussions with Ryan Stokes, Don   Haverman, and Davis Equipment.   Tom Winkel MaxYieId Cooperative

column168: CGTX 30210 was noted with the odor of mercaptan in the area of the car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Hepaco, Inc., responded and found a vapor release at the liquid valve flange.  Investigation developed that the shipper used odorized flammable gas (propane) to develop 20 pounds psi of pressure to off-load the gasoline from the tank car.  The 20 pounds of pressure was left in the car when it was released to transportation as a residue shipment.  The material leaking from the base flange of the liquid valve was residue odorized propane.  There was no release of the liquid residue gasoline.    The flammable gas was flared off reducing the pressure inside the car to zero pounds psi stopping the release.

column168: Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was involved in a household hazardous waste collection event in which homeowners have an opportunity to discard hazardous materials found in their homes such as oil, paints, gasoline, etc. at a central collection location.  At the conclusion of the collection event, the materials are prepared for transportation to a licensed waste management facility for disposal.  During the transportation phase of the operation, a 55 gallon container of flammable liquids developed a hole in the bottom of the drum allowing approximately 30 gallons of material to escape from the container onto the floor of the van trailer.  Approximately 20 gallons escaped from the trailer onto the asphalt roadway.  Upon discovering the release, the driver took immediate actions to prevent the continued release of the material by turning the drum over and spreading a suitable absorbent material onto the released material.  The local fire and police departments were called as was the Texas Department of Environmental Quality (RPT. # 20073969).  Clean Harbors dispatched a crew to the scene to respond to the leaking container.  While en route, the Conroe Police Department contracted a 3rd party emergency response company to initiate the clean-up process in order to open the lane of traffic that was blocked.  Please note that the roadway itself was not shut down but rather a lane of traffic.  Crews from Clean Harbors and Milstead Environmental absorbed all free liquids, containerized all spill debris and product that was released to both the roadway and the trailer floor.  All spill clean-up debris was placed into appropriate containers and sent for disposal to a licensed waste management facility.  The damaged container was also placed into a suitable salvage drum and continued to the intended waste management facility.
column169: In order to rpevent a recurrence of this incident, the employees involved in the preparation and shipment of household hazardous wastes for shipment have been re-instructed to inspect each container before it is used to insure that there is no visible sign of damage or questinable integrity.  Any containers found to be questionable are to be placed out of servce and sent for either disposal or recycle.

column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: CONX 1215 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard was reported with product dampness on the top side shell near the top fitting area. Product odor emanating from CONX 1215 was also reported. CONX 1215 was carefully isolated in the railyard. No ground impact of product was reported. The shipper was notified to inspect this tank car and ensure proper securement. In the morning of 11/20/07, a shipper contract responder inspected CONX 1215. The liquid valve's closure cap was not applied. The camlock closure cap when applied prevented the protective housing cover from being fully closed. The contract responder applied a shorter pipe nipple and secured the closure cap for the liquid valve around 0930 hrs. MST on 11/20/07. During the responder's securement process, an estimated 50 gallons of product was spilled via the liquid valve fittings and the responder reported this spillage to local BNSF management. A BNSF contract responder excavated the impacted ground soil and ballast. The excavated material was placed inside 55 gallon drums for appropriate disposal.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: TILX 400750 in the railyard was reported venting heavily from the top of this DOT 105J500W tank car. The venting ebbed after the product within TILX 400750 auto-refrigerated (iced). An initial inspection of TILX 400750 revealed that the 486 psi frangible disc had partially ruptured, rather than fully ruptured. The shipper replaced the frangible disc and sent the failed disc to the manufacturer for analysis. After the venting stopped, TILX 400750 was placed at the consignee's location for future unloading. It may take 3 to 5 weeks for the remaining product to warm and elevate the internal tank car pressure to 200 psi, a level for safe unloading. The shipper plans on replacing all frangible discs that are installed in similar constructed tank cars within their leased fleet.

column168: On November 21, 2007, at approximately 0325 hours, a railway tankcar IAPX 1045, loaded with Argon, refrigerated liquid, nonflammable gas, UN1951, was reported leaking at the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) Shreveport Louisiana yard. The tank car was discovered leaking from the liquid valve that was left open and the spring tensioner off of valve handle . The KCSR representative responded to the site closing the valve, applied tensioner stopping the release.  There were no injuries, no damage to the environment.          CODE: 117  NARRI: 5(5+1+0)x(3+0)=90
column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column169: This customer booked the cargo as non-hazardous (Batteries NOS) with our company on 10/04/2007, and the cargo was sailed with our operated vessel as non-hazardous from the port of Newark on 10/16/2007, and the vessel arrived at the port of Hong Kong on 11/17/2007.  On 11/12/2007, we were advised by the customer that the cargo was contained hazardous materials.  On the same date, we were also informed this undeclared dg cargo incident to our Hong Kong office.  According to them, this ccommodity was the controlled commodity by the Hong Kong authority under "Import of Used Electrical and Electronic appliance having Hazardous components or constituents (HKG)".  Furthermore, the HKG side checked and advised of rejection for discharging the cargo at HKG due to the cargo was containing plastic scraps with some parts of old batteries and PC monitor.  The HKG side's final comment was returning the cargo to the original place of loading.          This container had no hazardous placards, therefore our HKG side made arrangement to place the proper hazardous placards (based on the UN number appeared on the submitted dg declarations from the shipper in the US; although the dg paper work was not in compliance with the regulations, and we are still awaiting a valid dg declaration as of this date), in order for shipping back the dg container to the US.     For shipping back the dg cargo into the US (Neward port), the booking number had been changed to 455957308A (from the original bkg number 606853594A) and loaded with the same vessel with the different voyage number.  This vessel ETA at Newark port will be on 12/18/2007.     After the cargo returning back to the US, we are going to arrange for having a survey and obtaining a suvey report with possible photos as a result.

column168: Container DVRU 16381 8-4 was rejected by BNSF Railroad because the blocking & bracing didn’t meet AAR standards. CMA-CGN steamship line had it brought to our yard for correction. On Thursday afternoon, 11/02/07 at about 2:00 p.m. my assistant accidentally nicked one of the hazmat drums in this load while he was nailing the final blocking and bracing. We put tape over the hole and laid the drum on it side to control the leak. I doubt that we lost % of an ounce of fluid. We cleaned around the hole with a rag and patched the hole with Permatex, which is recommended for patching gas tanks and automobile radiators and it is holding. We placed the damaged drum in a 95 gal over-pack drum along with absorbent material. We are currently waiting for permission from the consignee to forward the drum to them.
column169: While the accident itself was a very strong lesson, I did review proper blocking & bracing and nailing procedures the employee.

column168: After morning preparation of the load our driver left our yard at 113 Illinois Lane Rhome, TX. 76078. He was traveling east on FM407 then turned north on FM2264 when turning on FM2264 a tote shifted with a hose hooked up. The valve was put in a bind from the hose causing the valve to break in the threads letting the Foamatron EFP-1406 leak out. Our driver continued to drive north on FM2264 not knowing the chemical was leaking. The driver then turned into the Joe Thurman #3 lease for Devon made a circle and saw the leak trail. He then got out to check, finding the broken valve. The driver called his supervisor David Siegfried. David called Garner Environmental Services to clean up the spill. Devon called Chico Auto Parts and Service and Chico mitigated the spill on the Devon location.Chico Auto Parts and Serice mitigated the spill under the supervision of Devon. Eight (8) yards of soil was removed and taken to the landfill. Garner Environmental called TAZ Environmental and TAZ cleaned up the spill on FM2264.
column169: After performing a root cause analysis we developed a corrective action plan consisting of the following steps:  1.Meeting with all drivers covering DOT Hazmat transportation regulation and DOT exemption 12412 highlighting the points that no hose can be hooked up to totes while in transit, and all containers must be secured to insure no movement of container is possible.  2.Driver training on DOT Hazmat transportation regulations and DOT exemption 12412.  3.Development of pre-trip check list to prevent future or similar occurrences.  4.Discuss this incident in Safety Meetings and Toolbox Safety Meetings.  5.Developed and posted Safety Alerts of the incident in all District Offices.

column25: Gulf Atlantic Floor Systems C/O National Polymers
column168: The initial report from the terminal manager to the company safety department stated 1 gallon of material had been released.The report came in at approx. 1600 hours. The driver was instructed to contain the material and cover with peat moss.At Approx. 1800 hours the incident was upgraded to 10 gallons of released product by a call from the local fire department to the terminal. The fire department indicated the material was contained and the vehicle could possibly been driven back to the terminal.The supervisor departed the terminal with another driver to pick up the unit. Upon arrival to the scene the incident had escalated to the local hazmat team being dispatched.The company immediately upon receipt of this information dispatched an emergency response team to clean up the release.The pails had turned over due to inadequate blocking and bracing.2 of the 5gallon pails had released onto the trailer floor due to the fall. The lids were crushed and broke open.The total release was managed in 8.5 hours. The driver was transported to a local hospital and later returned to the scene.The gymnastics event in the adjacent building was evacuated as a precautionary measure. The duration of the evacuation was 90 miutes, which would have been the conclusion of the event.Another person from the gymnastics event had left the event and returned via her parents complaining of symptoms related to the incident. She was evaluated by EMS personnel and transported to a Pittsburgh hospital as a precautionary measure due to a pre-existing condition.All the material(both damaged and non-damaged) was returned to the shipper.

column168: Van Trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environment Services, Inc arrived at Clean Harbors Facility, San Jose.   Upon arrival, Driver identified small amount of liquid leaking from the right rear corner of the trailer.   Driver immediately notified Plant Supervisor whom then immediately activated Clean Harbor’s Internal Contingency Plan.   Clean Harbors Facility Emergency Response Team donned Personal Protective Equipment and proceeded to identify the leak.   No spilled material was identified beyond the trailer and the entrance to the facility.   All free liquid was cleaned. An amount of less than one quart at the entrance to the facility was absorbed using absorbent material.   Upon further investigation, it was discovered that a small nail used to secure wood on a pallet punctured the drum which caused the release.   All spill debris was containerized in a suitable container and was sent for disposal at a fully licensed waste facility.
column169: In order to prevent a reoccurence, our Drivers have been reinstructed to continue inspecting pallets more diligently to ensure no exposed nails orscrewas are present and no potential for a drum puncture.

DRIVER STOPPED AT SPACE WAY TRUCK STOP TO TAKE HIS 10 HOUR BREAK. WHEN HE CAME OFF OF HIS BREAK, DID A WALK AROUND. NOTICED DRIP COMING FROM REAR OF THE TANK. HE PUT A BUCKET UNDER THE DRIP AND CALLED SAFETY DEPT. THEY NOTIFIED THE TRUCK STOP. THE LOST GAP FIRE DEPT RESPONDED AND LAUDERDALE COUNTY EMERGENCY DIRECTOR DAVID SHARP CAME ON SITE. SAFETY DEPT LINED UP FOR ANOTHER DRIVER TO BRING CLEAN TANK TO THE LOCATION TO TRANSFER THE LOAD ONTO.                                                           CLARENCE BEAN, SAFETY ENVIRONMENTAL WITH DANA, SUTTLES, LIQUID TRANSPORT, RESPONDED TO THE SPILL AND SUPERVISED THE TRANSFER.                                                                                                                     THE UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE, OUT OF JACKSON, MS CAME OUT PROVIDE LABOR AND MATERIALS TO CLEAN UP THE RESIDUE THAT GOT ON THE GROUND.                                                                                      THE RESIDUE WAS PUT INTO A 55 GALLON DRUM AND WILL SHIP OFF AS FLAMMABLE WASTE. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED, REPORT #20071118-00066 SAFETY MANAGER FOR LUCITE WAS CONTACTED FLOYD BILLINGS. THE TRAILER HAS BEEN CLEANED AND INSPECTED. THEY SAID THEIR IS A SMALL HOLE IN FRONT OF TANDEMS ON THE TRAILER.

Attempts to contact the shipper have not been successful at this time.

column168: On November 27, 2007, at 10:45 personnel in the CSXT ACCA Yard discovered UTLX 206060, a loaded tank car of Alcohol NOS leaking from the top of the car when the car was moved.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Hawkeye Renewable, was notified through Chemtrec  (CHEMTREC Report# 2007112700081).  Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a 5 bolt manway with 3 manway bolts less than tool tight and 1 bolt found in the down position.  Hepaco personnel tightened all manway bolts.  The leak was secured and the car released for transport.  No special switching move was required.    5(5+3+0) * (2+0) = 80  Cause code=200

column168: APPROXIMATELY 1630 ON 11-15-07, OUR DRIVER WAS NOTIFIED BY A PASSING MOTORIST THAT A LIQUID SUBSTANCE WAS LEAKING FROM OUR TRAILER. SINCE WE ARE AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY, OUR DRIVER NOTIFIED US IMMEDIATELY, AND IMMEDIATELY A CLEAN-UP CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. ONCE THE TRAILER WAS OPENED, THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS FOUND, A 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM. THE DRUM APPEARED TO HAVE PUNCTURE HOLES TOWARDS THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN 85 GALLON OVERPACK. SPEEDY-DRY WSA USED TO ABSORB ANY LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. PA DEP WS ON-SCENE AND DIRECTED THAT SPEEDY - DRY WAS THROWN DOWN AMONGST THE LEAVES AND DEBRIS ALONGSIDE THE ROADWAY. ONCE THE MATERIAL WAS SUFFICIENTLY ABSORBED, THE SOLVENT - CONTAMINATED DEBRIS WAS COLLECTED AND PLACED INTO A SEPERATE DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. THE OVERPACK DRUM WAS ABLE TO CONTINUE ON WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE LOAD TO THE DESIGNATED WASTE FACILITY.

THE DRIVER WAS THEN TOLD THAT THE TRAILER WAS BEING REJECTED BECAUSE IT WAS A SIDE UNLOADER INSTEAD OF A REAR UNLOADER, THE DRIVER FORGOT TO SECURE THE DOME COVER WHEN HE LEFT THE PLANT. A PHILADELPHIA, PA POLICE OFFICER OBSERVED MATERIAL SPILLING FROM THE TRAILER ON TO THE I-95 SOUTH EXIT RAMP FOR ALLEGHENY AVE. CARRIER CONTACT REACT ENVIRONMENTAL WHO CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THE EXIT RAMP WAS REOPENED AT APPROXIMATELY 1630 HOURS.
column169: THE DRIVER HAS GONE THROUGH A RETRAINING PROCESS EMPHASIZING TOTAL SECUREMENT OF THE TRAILER LOADED OR EMPTY.

column168: AMERIGAS DRIVER MIKE TIPTON HAD MADE A RESIDENTIAL DELIVERY AND WAS IN ROUTE TO NEXT CUSTOMER.  TRAVELING ON A 2/AVE NARROW (16') COUNTY ROAD AT APPROX 50 MPH (SPEED LIMIT WAS 55) HE SEES AN APPROACHING PROPANE DELIVERY TRUCK WHICH HE ESTIMATES WAS ALSO TRAVELING APPROX 50 MPH MIKE LOCKED UP THE BRAKES THE OTHER TRUCK CAUGHT HIS REAR AXLE.    THE IMPACT OF THE TWO VEHICLES SNAPPED A BRASS FITTING THAT COME OUT OF THE VAPOR ELIMINATOR FOR THE METER.  THERE WAS A DISCHARGE OF PROPANE BOTH LIQUID & VAPOR.  MIKE SHUT OFF THE VALVE PRIOR TO THE METER & THE LEAK STOPPED.  APPROX 2 GALS LOST TO ATMOSPHERE.
column169: THE DIRECT CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS THE ACCIDENT WITH THE TRUCK.  WE COULD ADD SUPPORTS TO THE PIPING & HOSES ON THE REAR DECK.  HOW MANY IS ENOUGH?

column168: Tractor-trailer loaded with 8000 gallons of ethanol left roadway and rolled over, causing spill of 5760 gallons of ethanol into road ditch and surrounding area. Big Stone City, SD. fire department responded as well as South Dakota Highway Patrol and Grant County, SD. Sheriff's Department. Rollover caused driver to be admitted to Ortonville, MN. hospital. Ethanol spilled from puncture in side of trailer caused by accident as well as escaped from manholes on top of trailer as trailer was upside down.
column169: CHS installed lane departure systems in all company trucks to alert drivers when they are close to leaving roadway. Post accident interview was held with driver to determine what he experienced that may have caused the truck to leave the roadway.

column168: WHILE LOADING, A TOTE WAS PUNCTURED BY FORKLIFT BLADE NEAR THE BASE. PER SHIPPER’S RECOMMENDATION AND AUTHORIZATION, A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TRANSFERRED THE ENTIRE PRODUCT OUT OF THE DAMAGED TOTE INTO A SALVAGE DRUMS. LINED SALVAGE DRUMS, EACH PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED, WERE USED FOR THE CLEAN-UP AND AFFECTED MATERIALS. THE DAMAGED EMPTY TOTE AND THE DRUMS ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT,WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE  COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

column168: The box was loaded into a FedEx DG ULD. After the ULD was loaded on to our aircraft, it was found to have a very strong odor. The ULD was offloaded and downloaded. The box was opened to reveal a cylinder with two valves, neither valve had positive closure. In addition the box had no absorbent material, no barrier bag, and styrofoam peanuts, some of which melted, were used as cushioning material.The package was placed in a salvage drum. The FAA was notified, I spoke to SA at 2220 hrs CST on 11/30/2007. The freight is being held pending an FAA inspection. The shipper was trained by FedEx in SanJose, Ca in January 2006, but the person who prepared the inner package cannot be verified as having training.

WHEN OUR DRIVER COMPLETED UNLOADING HIS TRAILER HE STARTED THE PROCESS OF BREAKING DOWN HIS HOSES. THERE IS A BALL VALVE ON THE DISCHARGE VALVE THAT ALLOWS A DRIVER TO RELIEVER AIR PRESSURE IN HIS HOSES. THE DRIVER FAILED TO MAKE SURE THAT THE BALL VALVE WAS CLEAR OF DEBRIS AND FULLY OPENED. WHEN HE WENT TO DISCONNECT HIS HOSE, THERE WAS PRESURE STILL IN THE LINES AND A MIST OF PRODUCT SPRAYED OUT OF THE HOSES AND ONTO THE CUSTOMERS BUILDING. THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT WAS ESTIMATED AT AROUND ONE OUNCE. THE DRIVER AND CUSTOMER WIPED THE PRODCUT OFF OF THE BUILDING AND FINISHED BREAKING DOWN THE HOSES. THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO CHEMTREC.
column169: THE DRIVER RETURNED FROM HIS LOAD AND WS IMMEDIATELY BOUGHT IN FOR REFRESHER TRAINING. HE WAS RE-TRAINED AND SHOWED THE PROPER WAY TO DISCONNECT HIS HOSES AND ACCOUNT FOR BACK-PRESSURE IN THE LINESE. HE THEN DEMOSTRATED THE PROCESS TO US AND WE RELEASED HIM BACK INTO SERVICE. HE WAS ALSO SHOWED HOW TO INSPECT THE BALL VALVE TO VERIFY THAT IT IS WORKING PROPERLY AND FREE OF ANY DEBRIS. THIS EVENT WILL BE DISCUSSED AT OUR NEXT QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETING AND USED AS A LEARNING TOOL.

column42: HYDROGEN, PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 40 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: Our driver made a delivery to our customer's storage tank. There was more product in our cargo tank than the customer's storage tank could hold.  The customer's employees were monitoring the level indication in their control room while our driver stayed at the cargo tank outlet valve.  The customer employee was to let our driver know when the level reached 80% in their storage tank.  At the 70% level our driver started to close the cargo tank outlet valve.  The next thing he noticed was product starting to come out of the storage tank overflow.  He immediately closed the cargo tank outlet valve.  The customer reported the storage tank level indication went from 77% to 100% almost immediately.  It was estimated less than 5 gallons overflowed into the containment dike.
column169: We will work with the customer to help insure our cargo tank only contains enough product that will fit into their storage tank for future deliveries.  The customer will check out their storage tank level device.

column42: HYDROGEN, PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 40 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: Our driver arrived at the customer location and confirmed with the customer that the tank would hold 800 gallons of product.  As the tank was being filled our driver and the customer monitored the storage tank digital gauge.  While the gauge indicated the tank could still hold more product, the gauge started to react unusually and product started to come out the top of the tank.  Our driver stopped flow to the tank.  Only 600 to 700 gallons were unloaded into the tank when it started to overflow.  It was estimated 10 to 15 gallons of product spilled into the containment area.  The customer diluted the spilled material and drained onto their treatment system.
column169: We will confirm that the customer checks out and repairs their storage tank level gauge.

column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: Driver arrived at shipper for loading. Shipper personnel loaded cargo tank by opening dome and transferred lading through dome opening.  After transfer complete, loader secured dome and released vehicle.  After release was discovered an inspection of the dome revealed that a washer on the wing nut securing the dome had fallen between the dome sealing edge and the gasket surface preventing a proper seal. This was corrected by the driver before proceeding.  Environmental response contractor arrived on scene to provide cleanup.

column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: Evidence at the scene and statement of the Driver indicates the following occurred:  The Driver was traveling south on Cabin Creek Road, Cabin Creek, WV, when he ran off the road on the right side.  He attempted to regain control of the vehicle while off the roadway and it overturned coming to rest in the middle of the roadway.  The roll-over caused the Diesel Fuel tank to rupture spilling 300 gallons of diesel fuel.
column169: Driver re-training.  The Driver's description of the accident was that he allowed his right front tire to run off the shoulder of the road where there was a significant drop off from the pavement.  In his attempts to steer the truck back onto the road, he lost control of the steering which resulted in the truck weight shifting and causing the subsequent roll-over.  This incident was a result of Driver error, and therefore, we have re-instructed the Driver and all other Drivers that travel that route to be cautious of the low shoulders.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was enroute to Clean Harbors's Los Angeles Vehicle terminal when the driver discovered that a small amount of material was leaking from the rear door of his trailer.  The driver immediatley pulled over and placed a containment device under the rear of the trailer.  The door was opened and it was discovered that a 55 gallon container had a crack on the lower portion of the drum allowing material to escape to the floor of the trailer and the absphalt roadway.  The driver immediatley called his home dispatcher and local emergency services.  An internal emergency response crew was dispacthed to the scene where they proceeded to remediate the material released.  The response crew utilized a suitable absorbent material to absorb all freee liquids and containerized the spill debris into suitable containers for ultimate disposal.  The floor of the trailer was also decontaminated as well.  The damaged container was placed into a suitable salvage drum and it, along with all clean-up debris was sent for disposal to a fully licensed waste management facility.  Prior to departing from the scene, authorization to depart was granted by the Vernon, CA Fire Department.  At the time the emergency crew was dispatched, both the California Emergency Services was notified as was the National Response Center.
column169: A review of the incident indicated that the package appeared to fail due to age.  At the time of loading, the containers were inspected and appeared to be in acceptable condition.  The containers were loaded into the vehicle ans secured using mechanical load locks.  The driver responsible for loading the continers has been re-instructed to insure that a thorough inspection is made of each package as it is loaded.  If any defect or suspect container is encountered, appropriate corrective actions must be taken before accepting for transport.

column168: Began loading cargo tank and noticed leak at bottom discharge valve. Our normal loading procedure is to have the internal valve closed and external valve open. This confirms internal valve is holding. The external valve is closed after loading. The internal valve was inadvertantly open when began filling since liquid came out immediately when began filling cargo tank. The loader immediately stopped loading and closed the valve.
column169: The loaders have been trained to also look at the internal valve stem to confirm internal valve is closed. They have also been trained again on how to close internal valve. The carrier confirmed they vacuum test the internal valve every time the cargo tank is cleaned and internal valve is hydrostatically tested once per year.

column168: Driver had just started to transfer product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank using his pump.  When product got to the pump, it leaked out the bottom of the pump.  The driver had forgotten to close the petcock on the pump prior to starting the transfer.  Driver stopped the transfer, closed the valve and proceeded with the offload.
column169: Driver did not follow procedure to verify that all valves were closed before he started the transfer.  He has received performance enhancement training since the incident.

column168: This was an undeclared shipment with no release. The shipper was Swisher International, a known shipper. Freightwas tendered as a Roll Label Machine in a crate, and picked up at shipper's place of business. The freight wastendered to Amerijet in Jacksonville, FL (JAX) for delivery in Trinidad, W.I. (POS) Shipment was off loaded inTrinidad, W.I. and moved to customs for clearance. On 11/22/2007, we received an e-mail from our agent inTrinidad, W.I, stating a customs officer states "I certify having examined one (1) box and found contents to be one (1)roll label unit, correct as invoiced and as entered. However various machine parts were found for which properinvoices should be submitted stating unit price for same. In addition two (2) rolls of printed labels and two (2) gallonsof Phosphoric Acid were found. Values for same are to be submitted."When Allstates WorldCargo, Inc. received this e-mail, we immediately contacted the shipper, Swisher International,for an explanation. Swisher International's shipping department advised that they did not know anything about 2gallons of Phosphoric acid. They checked with the mechanic that packaged the shipment and he advised thatanother vendor requested him to consolidate the 2 gallons with his shipment to ship to the consignee. The mechanicadvised that he did not know the 2 gallons were hazardous. Swisher International immediately contacted the vendorwho sent the 2 gallons to them to request the proper hazardous material shipping description which is included in thisreport. There was not a spill of the hazardous material; however, it did move through the transportation systemwithout being disclosed as a hazardous shipment. (As such, for purposes of this Incident Report form, we haveconsidered the incident to have occurred in Jacksonville, FL, when the shipment was tendered to the airline, ratherthan in Trinidad, W.I., when the contents were discovered.)
column169: Allstates WorldCargo, Inc. has contacted the shipper, Swisher International and have reviewed the requirements ofbeing a known shipper and transportation regulations of shipping hazardous materials. They have been advised thatthey must have a hazardous material certified employee in order to ship hazardous material and that they mustdisclose to Allstates WorldCargo, Inc. when hazardous materials are being shipped. They must also provide theproper shipping documentation with the shipment for all hazardous materials.For the next six months, Allstates WorldCargo, Inc. will physically open and inspect all shipments from SwisherInternational before tendering to an airline in order to prevent future occurrences described above. AllstatesWorldCargo, Inc. will manifest the items shipped and compare to the bill of lading and commercial invoice providedby Swisher International. This will serve as a checklist for both Allstates WorldCargo, Inc. and Swisher Internationalto ensure accuracy on future shipments.

column168: DRIVER WAS HEADING WEST ON HWY 64 RETRUNING TO THE PLANT FROM A DELIVERY TO GOLDSBORO, NC. THE SUN WAS LOW IN THE SKY BELOW THE VISOR AND DIRECTLY IN THE DRIVERS EYES. (I WITNESSED THIS WHEN I WAS ON SITE EXACTLY 24 HOR LATER; BUTCH) THERE WAS SWIFT TRACTOR TRAILER (VAN) HALF WAY IN THE RIGHT LANE STOPPED BECAUSE HE HAD ABLOW OUT OF THE  RIGHT STEERING TIRE.  HE HAD HIS TRIANGLES OUT BUT THEY WERE NOT THE PROPER DISTANCE TO GIVE ANOTHER DRIVER TIME TO REACT.  THE DRIVER SAW THE TRUCK BUT DID NOT REALIZE IT WAS NOT OFF THE ROAD UNTIL IT WAS TOO LATE.  HE HIT THE LEFT REAR OF THE TRAILER WITH THE RIGHT FRONT OF B17.  THIS FOLDED THE STEERING TIRES UNDER AND B17 SKIDDED TO A STOP AT ABOUT 300.  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO CHAPEL HILL TO THE HOSPITAL TO BE CHECKED OUT.  THE COLLISION SHEARED OFF THE PIPING AND VALVES ON THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE UNIT.  IT LEFT THE CLOSING PORTION OF THE INTERNAL VALVE INTHE TANK,THIS HELD FOR THE MOST PART BUT DID ALLOW A LITTLE VAPOR TO ESCAPE.  THIS AREA WAS ENCASED BY A STEEL BOX BUILT BY AN OUTSIDE VENDOR WHERE THE UNIT COULD BE MOVED AND EVACUATED.

column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: On Friday, November 09, 2007 at approximately 0200 EST, a Quality Distribution Tanker trailer overturned on Rt 17in Goshen IN. The tanker was transporting a load of Duramac 50-5070 Alkyd Resin, of which 2,000 gallons spilledonto pavement, grass and into a nearby retention pond. At 1034 hrs, a clean tanker arrived on site and HMHTTCcrew performed a transfer of the remaining liquid in the damaged trailer to the new one. At 1252 hrs the transfer wascompleted and the response team began working on remediating the spilled product.At 1730 hrs on Friday November 9, 2007, the response team cleared location. 5-6 loads of sand were laid on the spillareas and into the affected storm drain. All contaminated sand was stockpiled, profiled for proper disposal onMonday November 12, 2007 and picked up and disposed of on Tuesday November 13, 2007.

column169: BETTER SECUREMENT OF CAP ON DRUMS. DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING OF PAILS, DRUMS, TOTES OR MISCELLANEOUS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING. THE SEAMS ON THE PACKAGING MUST BE ABLE TO HOLD LIQUID WITHOUT LEAKING OUT. THE DURABILITY OF A DRUM, PAIL, BAGS AND, OR TOTE MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION. IMPORTANT THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE. TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFELY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER, PAGKAGING, MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED. DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT.
