column168: A northbound (westward) BNSF intermodal stack train derailed eight intermodal multiplatform flatcars on UPRR single main track when exiting the west portal of Tunnel No. 7 just east of UPRR Cliff station. The cause of this derailment was attributed to a broken rail at a field weld on the track just inside the tunnel at the west portal. An intermodal flatcar with intermodal container TRLU 635881 derailed with TRLU 635881 on its side. TRLU 635881 came to rest hanging over a steep embankment. After TRLU 635881 was moved to a safe and level location, a BNSF contractor inspected the lading inside. All eighty 55 gallon steel closed head drums inside TRLU 635881 incurred denting from derailment dynamics. One drum sustained a four inch cut at the mid-upper portion of the drum sidewall and released some product. All these drums were placed into secure overpack drums and loaded into another container for transport continuation. The spillage inside the damaged TRLU 635881 was cleaned and the small amount of product that leaked outside the intermodal container onto the ground was remediated.

column168: Fred Grant, Manager of Terminal Operations, reported a switchman was exposed to denatured alcohol during switching operations inthe North Yard in Denver, CO. Mr. Grant stated the alcohol was splashed onto the switchman from a residue tankcar with a loose cap and advised the employee was transported to North Suburban Medical Center in Denver, CO, where he was treated and released. On11 /15/2007 At 09:50 AM, Kim Keeling, Manager of Hazardous Materials, stated the tankcar was interchanged from the Rock Island Railroad and identified the railcar as Tankcar UTLX 205039. Mr. Keeling confirmed tankcar was received with the protective housing closed but not sealed and the liquid valve was open with an unsecured plug. Also, the bottom outlet cap was unsecured (Less than tooltight). State and federal regulatory agencies were notified. At 01:48 PM, Keeling advised the car was secured by a local mechanical employee.

At 11:46 PM, Miller reported the tankcar defects were repaired. At 11:55 PM, Miller advised a small amount of contaminated ballast was removed from the site.

Josh Anderson, Manager of Yard Operations, reported empty Tank car DOWX 4884 was releasing product on Track 98 of the Livonia, , Rail yard. State notifications were issued. Upon inspection Robinson found that the top operated bottom outlet valve was partially open. He secured the valve by turning the operating stem approximately two turns.

column168: I was traveling west bound on 1-26 approximately 1 mile before the 199 exit, when I noticed a car to my right come up on stopped traffic. The car could not stop so it went into the emergency lane, then it appeared that the driver over corrected the car to the left and crossed the right lane into the center lane where it ran under my trailer. I pulled over to the emergency lane and noticed some gasoline from my tanker leaking. I shut down the emergency switch on my trailer, then called 911. Upon arrival of the fire department they sprayed foam on the highway and truck to keep product from igniting. The accident occurred at approximately 6:20 pm and final transfer of product to another tanker was completed at 2:45 am. Two lanes of 1-26 were shut down until 12:45 am, then from 12:45 until 2:45 the three west bound lanes were shut down by the fire department and highway patrol for the transfer of the gasoline.

column168: Kim Keeling, Manager of Environmental Field Operations, stated loaded Tankcar TILX 160191 released product during movement. Mr. Keeling stated the product had not reached the ground and was located in east departure six of the Bailey Yard on North Platte, NE. Mr. Keeling inspected the railcar and stated the cause of the release was from a ruptured flange disc and advised he was unable to determine when the disc ruptured. The disc cap was not secured and was laying in the open position with the disc ruptured. State regulatory agencies were notified. Mr. Keeling advised the disc was replaced with a new one and the cap was secured, pinned and sealed. Mr. Keeling further advised the tankcar was placed in the extension of the runner at the east end of the east departure yard. At 01:34 PM, Keeling advised the decontamination operation would be performed on the morning of 11/21/2007. In addition, Mr. Keeling stated the tankcar will be placed in a temporary hold until decontaminated and neutralized. On 11/21/2007, at 12:57 PM, Keeling advised the tankcar was decontaminated and returned to operations at 09:45 AM.

column168: Dan McBride, Manager GTS, reported a release of liquid from the bottom of container GLDU 92400 located on a trailer at Lot B of the Settegast lntermodal Yard in Houston, TX. Mr. McBride stated there were no injuries, no exposures and no waterways impacted. He further stated the release was approximately four feet by eight feet on asphalt in Lot B of the Settegast Yard. Mr. McBride stated the reponding manager would be Forrest King, Manager of Intermodal Operations, who contacted Chemtrec and stated no response was necessary. Captain Villasana, Houston Fire Department, was notified and was told no response was necessary. Geoffrey Reeder, Environmental Site Manager, was notified and responded. Chemtrec notification was made. State and Federal notifications were made. At 04:57 PM, Shannon Mizell, American President Lines, was conferenced with Geoffrey Reeder, Environmental Site Manager, who stated a clear, odorless, liquid, was on the ground and discussed how the remediation would be completed. At 06:59 PM, Reeder advised the container was moved to another location and surrounded with absorbent material.  Further examination found that some of the material was wet. It looked as though the material had been wet when loaded. The liquid leaking out was acidic. Absorbent material was used to stop the leak. The material was replaced in the container and returned to the origin location.

column168: David Sperow, Manager of Yard Operations, requested an inspection of a loaded Tankcar GATX 201623 due to fresh wet marks on the outside of the tankcar. Manager Hazardous Materials, Mike Grant inspected the tankcar. No indications of release on exterior of car. Air valve was open and plug was not in place on valve. Closed valve, secured plug, sealed protective housing cover.

Shirley Tunge, Lead Carman, reported yard personnel observed a possible release of product from Tankcar TILX 193438 due to a dragging handle on the gate. She requested an inspection of the tankcar which was located on Track 565 in the North Platte Yard at Mile Post 290.84 of the North Platte Terminal, in North Platte, NE. Ms. Tunge advised no injuries, no illnesses, and no waterways were involved with this incident. Kim Keeling, Manager Environmental Field Operations, was notified and responded. At 09:44 AM, Keeling advised that the pin of the handle was unsecured which resulted in the release. State and federal regulatory agencies were notified. At 1 0:32 AM, Keeling reported the securement pin for the valve handle was not sealable and bad ordered. Mr. Keeling advised the valve was wedged open previously by contact with the ground, which caused the release. Mr. Keeling stated the handle was placed back in the closed position with the pin secured temporarily until the tankcar reached its final destination where it would be off-loaded and repaired. Mr. Keeling advised oil dry was placed on the spilled product and would be swept up for disposal.

column168: The driver of the unit had stopped at a truck stop and observed a viscous liquid on the rear of the trailer unit Land Span then contacted Environmental Management (Laud Span emergency response provider) and requested a response to the release (Enviommeutal Management Job #25487). Environmental Management contacted Eco-Logical Environmental Services, Inc. (ELliS) an Environmental Management approved environmental subcontractor and requested that ELES respond. The ELES response team arrived on site. It was observed that the material had impacted the trailer floor and the outer edge of the trailer. The release did not impact the ground. It was observed that a pallet with six (6) 5-gallon plastic containers of resin solution were located at the rear of the the trailer. A large wooden spool that was located in front of the pallets had rolled back onto the pallet and crushed one of the 5-gallon containers. ft was observed that the spooi had been braced but the weight of the spooi broke through the bracing (inefficient blocking and bracing) A small puncture hole on the bottom of the 5-gallon container was observed. Approximately 1 gallon of resin product had been released. The release had impacted the pallet and a 3-foot by 1-foot area of the trailer floor. The containers were removed from the pallet and the pallet was cleaned. The damaged container was overpacked in a drum. The drum was labeled and placed back on the trailer. Absorbent material was then applied to the imapcted area on the trailer floor. The trailer floor and the rear (exterior) of the trailer were cleaned. The absorbent material and debris ware then placed into a 5-gallon container. The unit was then released. The 5-gallon container of contaminated absorbents and debris was transported back to the ELES facility pending disposal arrangements. On December 7,2007 the one 5-gallon container of contaminated absorbents was transported to Southwest Landfill TX, LP (Allied Waste) in Canyon, Texas for disposal.

column168: At 02:00 PM on 11-5-07, Frank Larch, Manager of Hazardous Materials, noted a dry, white in color product on the top and sides of tank car GATX 20379, located on Track 10 of the Englewood Railyard, in Houston, TX. Upon inspection of the car Mgr. Lerch noted a failed frangible disk in the safety vent assembly, the top operated bottom outlet valve open 1/2 turn, and the top operated bottom outlet valve packing gland nut to be loose 3/4 turn.   Upon replacing the ruptured frangible disk with a similar BS&B 1651b disk, closing the top   operated bottom outlet valve, and tightening the packing gland nut to the top operated bottom outlet valve, the car was secure for movement. Mgr. Lerch had the car set out to be cleaned. Mgr. Lerch then contact shipper plant manager Dennis Tooke of Southern lonics, and advised him of the condition the car was found in, and corrective actions taken.   Mr. Tooke advised the he would have   plant personnel respond the following day to clean the car. At 11:00AM on 11-6-07, Southern lonics personnel arrived on site, and cleaned the car. Car was then released to continue onto destination without further incident. There were no drains, waterways impacted, or reported injuries resulting from this release. Cause of the failed frangible disk unknown, as there were no signs of rough handling to the car.

column168: Tom McGahan, Yardmaster, reported Tankcar NATX 29568 released an unknown amount of product onto the ground at Yard One Track 223 inside the Bailey Yard in North Platte, NE. Mr. McGahan stated the product was released from the bottom side of the tank and confirmed there were no waterways affected. Kim Keeling, Manager Hazardous Materials, was notified and responded. State notifications were issued.   At 10:39 AM, Kim Keeling, Manager Hazardous Materials, advised he was unable to make repairs to the   tankcar. He further advised that there was a stripped bolt and a possible bad gasket on the bottom outlet valve, and the outlet valve flange would not seal properly. Mr. Keeling stated the tankcar would be moved to the freight house until a transfer could be arranged. Mr. Keeling advised the release had not been stopped, however; less than one gallon of product had been released.   At 12:42 PM,   Keeling advised that the transfer would take place on 1 1/19/2007. A drum liner was taped around the valve to prevent vapor and   product from escaping , the bottom of the liner was placed into a nine gallon bucket to prevent any release to the environment.   On   11/20/07 at 07:34 PM, transfer of product from tankcar NATX 29568 to tankcar UTLX 204243 by Hazmat Response Incorporated personnel. In addition, Mr Keeling stated Railcar NATX 29568 was marked to return to home shop for repairs with “Do Not Load” decals placed on the equipment. A one time movement approval was applied for on 11/21/2007 by the shipper of Hwkey Renewable Energy

column168: At 11:03 PM on 11-31-07, Frank Lerch, Manager Hazardous Materials was contacted by the RMCC, and advised that David Jarreau, Manager of Terminal Operations, reported tank car UTLX 85872 released a small amount of product from the top of the car while it was being switched. Car was located in the Livonla Railyard on departure track 302 located at Mile Post 113.00 of the Livonia Subdivision in Livonia, LA.   Upon being notified, Mgr. Lerch spoke to MTO Jarreau who indicated that he would have the car switched   out, and isolated in the hazmat track for further handling. Mgr. Lerch then contacted the RMCC, and requested that shipper notification be made via Chem-Trec.   At 11:56PM, Mgr. Larch spoke with shipper representative Doug Rowland, Hazmat Coordinator for   Millennium Petroleum, and advised him of the release and corrective actions taken. Arrangements were then made for United States   Environmental Services out of Prairieville, LA to respond, make repairs to the car, and remediate the affected area.   At 3:14AM on   12/1/07 was advised by United States Environmental Services personnel that the cause of the release was a worn and shifted manway gasket and three in position, but not wrench tight manway swing bolts. Upon replacement of the manway gasket, resecurement of the manway cover, cleaning and neutralizing the top and sides of the car, it was released for transportation, and continued onto destination without further incident.   There were no drains, waterways impacted, or reported injuries resulting from this release.

column168: Bruce Strait loaded his trailer with 8500 gallons gasoline in Altoona, PA, and headed to State College. While driving, on Route 350 south of Warriors Mark, PA he lost control of the tractor trailer. The trailer made contact with the guard rail, and it caused the trailer to flip onto its side. It came to rest on the birm of the road with punctures in at least the front compartment. An emergency worker who happened to be coming the other way, helped the driver get out of the wreckage. The package failure was caused by the ragged edges of the guard rail, and it is believed that the trailer had damage the entire length of the structure. The gasoline then caught fire, there was an explosion, and the heat of the fire destroyed the entire tractor & trailer. The fire lasted for approximately one hour, and the amount of gasoline that escaped the fire and went into the ground can not be determined. Warriors Mark Fire Company, PA State Police, And Huntingdon County Emergency Response team all responded to the 911 call. The driver was stabilized and transported to Altoona Hospital. The fire was controlled, and contained to an area of approximately 70 yards by 50 yards.

column168: DRIVER #1 STATEMENT: SEE ATTACHED WRITTEN STATEMENT.   DRIVER #2 STATEMENT: SEE ATTACHED WRITTEN STATEMENT.   WITNESS #1 THE TAN SUV WAS IN THE RIGHT LANE AND THE TANKER TRUCK WAS IN THE LEFT LANE. THE TAN SUV CHANGED -LANES IN FRONT OF THE TANKER AND THE TANKER TRUCK TRIED TO AVOID THE SUV AND THAT IS WHEN IT BIT THE WALL AND THE BRIDGE. THERE WERE SPARKS AND IT WAS EXTREMELY LOUD.THERE IS NO WAY THEY DIDN’T KNOW THAT SOMETHING HAD HAPPENED. THE SUV DIDN’T STOP SO MY HUSBAND AND I FOLLOWED THE SUV TO GET A TAG. WE CONTACTED THE POLICE DISPATCHERS AND GAVE THEM THE INFORMATION.   TROOPER’S OPINION: UNITS 1 & N2 WERE WESTBOUND ON 1-70 AT MILEPOST #201.7. UNIT #1 WAS IN THE LEFT LANE. N2 WAS IN THE RIGHT LANE AND ATTEMPTED TO MARE A LANE CHANGE TO THE LEFT. N2 DID NOT HAVE SUFFICIENT CLEARANCE AND UNIT #1 HAD TO MAKE AN AVOIDING MANEUVER TO PREVENT CONTACTING 142. UNIT #1’S TRAILER SWUNG TO THE LEFT AND THE TIRES STRUCK THE CONCRETE MEDIAN BARRIER WALL AND THIS PUSHED THE TRAILER FLIP INTO THE BRIDGE PILLAR. THE TRAILER SIDESWIPED THE BRIDGE PILLAR CAUSING DAMAGE TO THE TRAILER RESULTING IN FUEL LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.   DRIVER #1 REGAINED CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE, PULLED TO THE RIGHT SHOULDER AND CONTACTED EMERGENCY SERVICES VIA TELEPHONE. N2 DID NOT STOP AT THE SCENE, HOWEVER STOPPED APPROXIMATELY SIX MILES LATER.

column168: At approximately 1125 hours, 23 November 2007, Andrew Shea, Apria Healthcare employee, was driving west on Route N, approximately .2 miles before County Road 140th SE in Buchanan, MO. Shea was driving an Apria Healthcare 2003 Isuzu FRR box truck, MO license #587761, Oxygen placarded and marker 1073,  when he dropped the curb side wheels onto the right shoulder of the road, over corrected, skidded across the centerline, continued skidding, and ran off the left side of the road, where it struck a ditch and overturned.    In response to Shea’s report the Missouri State Highway Patrol (3 units), the Easton Fire Department and the San Antonio Fire Department responded to the scene. They proceeded to close Route N between 140th and 144th, approximately ½ mile. Upon observing a white vapor coming from the truck the troopers had contacted the Region H, Homeland Security Response Team, Saint Joseph, MO for response.    At approximately 1300 hours Shea was transported to OHS-Compcare for treatment or pain in his right side by an Apria Healthcare employee.    At approximately 1330 hours the Region H, Homeland Security Response Team arrived on the scene with two vehicles and four individuals. They drove out though a field to approach the vehicle. Stanley Crockett, Apria Healthcare Branch Logistics Manager attempted to talk with them but they refused.     They proceeded to suit up two individuals in Level A fully encapsulated suits. At approximately 1430 hours they broke open the roof of the box on the tuck and began off loading cylinders (Oxygen, compressed) and other equipment from the truck. After they finished they advised the fire personnel that until the truck mounted vessel (Oxygen, refrigerated liquid) finished venting no one could approach the vehicle.     There did not appear to be any damage to the cryogenic vessel and the “venting” was a result of the vessel being on it’s side which did not allow the road relief valve to function properly. Stanley Crockett advised them that if they were going to wait for it to vent that way it would take several hours. They would need to open the vent valve to blow off pressure. They then requested Crockett respond to the truck and tell them where the vent valve was. Upon reaching the truck they had him enter the truck and open the vent valve. At that time he examined the vessel and determined that it had not been damaged or compromised in any way. He then opened the vent valve to relieve the pressure. Within approximately five minutes the vessel stopped venting. He was then advised that they could load up the equipment that had been off loaded.    By approximately 1500 hours tow trucks had righted the vehicle and towed it from the scene and the road was reopened.    It should be noted that there was no release of hazardous materials, other then what the hazmat team had vented off.     The justification for a four man hazmat response team to a possible oxygen spill is questionable, much less, 2.5 hours at the scen
